Great question! Here‚Äôs exactly how to connect your custom GPT chatbot (built in Next.js) with Framer using the Framer Code Component. This way, your chatbot runs on your website but is embedded seamlessly inside your Framer project UI.

üîó Option 1: Embed it in Framer via an Iframe
This is the easiest and most reliable way.

‚úÖ Step-by-step:
Deploy your chatbot

Push your project to GitHub (if not already)

Deploy it on Vercel (super simple if you already used Next.js templates)

You‚Äôll get a URL like: https://panth-chatbot.vercel.app

In Framer: Add an Embed Code Component

Drag a Code ‚Üí Embed component onto your canvas.

Paste this inside it:

<iframe
  src="https://panth-chatbot.vercel.app"
  style="width: 100%; height: 100%; border: none;"
></iframe>
Resize the component

Adjust the height (e.g., 400‚Äì600px) so the chat fits.

You can also style a floating chat icon that expands into this frame.

üéâ Done! Your chatbot is now inside your Framer site.

üß† Option 2: Use Framer‚Äôs Code Component (Advanced)
If you want to fully integrate the frontend logic of the chatbot into Framer using their React-based Code Component:

Move your chat UI into a single .tsx React component.

Strip out any server-related code and use a fetch call to hit your own backend (e.g., /api/chat on your deployed Next.js server).

Paste the final React component into Framer‚Äôs Code Component.

‚ö†Ô∏è Downside: Framer doesn't support server routes or long-running backend functions. So you still need to host your backend somewhere, and just call it from Framer.

‚úÖ Recommendation for You
Use Option 1 (iframe). It‚Äôs:

Free

Clean

Fast to set up

Works perfectly for your portfolio chatbot

